english:
  title: Preface to a Poem on Ascending High on the Ninth Day of the Ninth Month
  author: Sung Gan
  language: eng
  text: 'On the ninth day of the ninth month, my brothers and I gathered with Jeong Pil-dae, Ha Eung-cheon, Lee Yun-bo, and Kang Gyeong-chun. We brought wine and chicken, led five or six servants, and climbed the mountain west of our residence to hold a modest gathering. We followed the ancient custom of Yongsan, though our celebration perhaps exceeded it in refinement. The weather was clear and crisp, the sun had already set, and the evening drum sounded from the streets. The darkness grew profound. To the southwest, the mountain peaks rose in succession, some linked and jutting upward, others trailing and pooling like water, their blue and white hues flickering in and out of sight. Below the mountain gathered woodcutters at rest, shepherds singing, merchants with their boats, and fishermen with their lights—a thousand forms of life displaying themselves beneath this mountain. Looking northeast from our perch, the city walls and pavilions, the bustling markets sprawled before us, their images wavering like smoke and mist. Soon the moon rose, and the shadows lifted entirely. All that met the eye grew sharper, all that met the ear grew clearer. The brightness of the city shone magnificently, while a tranquil spirit of rivers and lakes pervaded the air. Had Ouyang Xiu himself witnessed this, surely he would have written of the union of two beauties. We filled our cups and drank until drunk, discoursing on ancient times, composing linked verses, dancing—so lost were we that we did not notice our caps falling to the ground until the Milky Way had already turned westward. Alas! In ages past, this mountain lay buried in wilderness, travelers merely glancing at it without pause. That it now reveals itself to us—is this Heaven''s kindness to us? Yet if this mountain''s revelation is Heaven''s work, then so too are the fortunes and misfortunes of all people Heaven''s work. Thus we should surrender ourselves wholly to Heaven''s will, not to the schemes of men. How can we anxiously chase after mere chance and never know the joy of a single day? Someone objected, saying: ''Indulgence and wandering are what the virtuous man warns against. How can you gentlemen abandon your duties and revel thus, yet cite the crude teachings of Zhuangzi and Liezi to justify yourselves?'' But does not the Book of Poetry say: ''Skillful in jest, yet causing no harm''? Our leisure here seeks only to invigorate the spirit. We do not scorn propriety and righteousness, nor do we boast falsely of being broad-minded while remaining forever outside the realm of sages and worthies. Such pretenders are not of our company. I have recorded all the linked verses composed by my friends, as a foundation for our reunion in future days, and have now given voice to ten poetic chapters.'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Ninth Day of the Ninth Month: A traditional festival in East Asian culture, marked by ascents to high places and reflection on impermanence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yongsan: A famous site from classical Chinese tradition associated with autumn excursions and poetry gatherings.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ouyang Xiu: A celebrated Song Dynasty scholar and writer known for essays combining observations of nature with philosophical reflection.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhuangzi and Liezi: Daoist philosophers whose teachings emphasize freedom and acceptance of natural ways.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Book of Poetry: One of the Five Classics of Confucianism, frequently cited as an authoritative source of wisdom.'
